<subSubSection id="C31265278D21015C82DEB326EC09F899" pageId="2" pageNumber="190" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BB736AC8D21015C82DEB326EC09F899" blockId="2.[151,1437,831,1864]" pageId="2" pageNumber="190">
<emphasis id="B97CEABE8D21015C82DEB326EF21F9F0" bold="true" box="[199,315,1588,1613]" pageId="2" pageNumber="190">Remarks.</emphasis>
This new species is similar in external appearance to 
<taxonomicName id="4C084D2F8D21015C818AB327EB5EF9F0" authority="Viraktamath &amp; Wesley" authorityName="Viraktamath &amp; Wesley" authorityYear="1988" box="[915,1348,1588,1613]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Nirvana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="190" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="striata">
<emphasis id="B97CEABE8D21015C818AB327EA24F9F1" box="[915,1086,1589,1612]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="190">Nirvana striata</emphasis>
Viraktamath &amp; Wesley
</taxonomicName>
but can be differentiated by the following characters: style with apophysis long, spine-like, aedeagus with spine-like apical sclerotization of the shaft, basal processes of dorsal apodeme foot-like, and subgenital plates about 
<date id="FFB6106C8D21015C86E0B36EEB0FF928" box="[1273,1301,1660,1685]" pageId="2" pageNumber="190">5x</date>
longer than broad. Also, the female seventh sternite has the hind margin medially notched in the new species but truncate in 
<emphasis id="B97CEABE8D21015C879BB3B3EEF2F961" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="190">
<taxonomicName id="4C084D2F8D21015C879BB3B3EEFEF961" authorityName="Viraktamath &amp; Wesley" authorityYear="1988" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Nirvana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="190" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="striata">N. striata</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
One other species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C084D2F8D21015C83C0B3D7EC2FF961" authorityName="Kirkaldy" authorityYear="1900" box="[473,565,1733,1756]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Nirvana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="190" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97CEABE8D21015C83C0B3D7EC2FF961" box="[473,565,1733,1756]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="190">Nirvana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C084D2F8D21015C805AB3D7EDF6F960" authority="Viraktamath and Wesley" authorityName="Viraktamath and Wesley" box="[579,1004,1732,1757]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Nirvana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="190" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peculiaris">
<emphasis id="B97CEABE8D21015C805AB3D7ECC9F961" box="[579,723,1732,1756]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="190">N. peculiaris</emphasis>
Viraktamath and Wesley
</taxonomicName>
from Northeast 
<collectingCountry id="F31F763C8D21015C86BDB3D6EAFAF960" box="[1188,1248,1732,1757]" name="India" pageId="2" pageNumber="190">India</collectingCountry>
, has paired short processes at the base of the anal tube but the processes of 
<taxonomicName id="4C084D2F8D21015C812AB3FBEDB1F942" authorityName="Naveed &amp; Zhang" authorityYear="2018" box="[819,939,1768,1792]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Nirvana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="190" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinosa">
<emphasis id="B97CEABE8D21015C812AB3FBEDB1F942" box="[819,939,1768,1792]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="190">N. spinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are much longer and the male genitalia are different in several other respects.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C31265278D21015C82DEB23DEB9CF8F5" box="[199,1414,1839,1864]" pageId="2" pageNumber="190" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BB736AC8D21015C82DEB23DEB9CF8F5" blockId="2.[151,1437,831,1864]" box="[199,1414,1839,1864]" pageId="2" pageNumber="190">
<emphasis id="B97CEABE8D21015C82DEB23DEF54F8F5" bold="true" box="[199,334,1839,1864]" pageId="2" pageNumber="190">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet “ 
<taxonomicName id="4C084D2F8D21015C805DB222EC83F8FA" authorityName="Naveed &amp; Zhang" authorityYear="2018" box="[580,665,1840,1863]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Nirvana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="190" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinosa">
<emphasis id="B97CEABE8D21015C805DB222EC83F8FA" box="[580,665,1840,1863]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="190">spinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” refers to the spine-like apical sclerotization of the aedeagal shaft.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
